{"id":"1806.09298","submitter":"Mikko Korhonen","authors":"Mikko Korhonen","title":"A counterexample to a conjugacy conjecture of Steinberg","comments":"to appear in Transform. Groups","journal-ref":"Transform. Groups, 25 (2020) 1209-1222","doi":"10.1007/s00031-019-09538-3","report-no":null,"categories":"math.GR math.RT","license":"http://arxiv.org/licenses/nonexclusive-distrib/1.0/","abstract":"  Let $G$ be a semisimple algebraic group over an algebraically closed field of\ncharacteristic $p \\geq 0$. At the 1966 International Congress of Mathematicians\nin Moscow, Robert Steinberg conjectured that two elements $a, a' \\in G$ are\nconjugate in $G$ if and only if $f(a)$ and $f(a')$ are conjugate in\n$\\operatorname{GL}(V)$ for every rational irreducible representation $f: G\n\\rightarrow \\operatorname{GL}(V)$. Steinberg showed that the conjecture holds\nif $a$ and $a'$ are semisimple, and also proved the conjecture when $p = 0$. In\nthis paper, we give a counterexample to Steinberg's conjecture. Specifically,\nwe show that when $p = 2$ and $G$ is simple of type $C_5$, there exist two\nnon-conjugate unipotent elements $u, u' \\in G$ such that $f(u)$ and $f(u')$ are\nconjugate in $\\operatorname{GL}(V)$ for every rational irreducible\nrepresentation $f: G \\rightarrow \\operatorname{GL}(V)$.\n","versions":[{"version":"v1","created":"Mon, 25 Jun 2018 06:15:29 GMT"},{"version":"v2","created":"Tue, 3 Sep 2019 10:25:27 GMT"}],"update_date":"2020-11-02"}
